{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S4zDGWxj5GE5vfazVYyxQQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Elasticsearch cluster is running with TLS (HTTPS on port 9200). The `es-http-tls` secret contains a CA cert, TLS cert, and TLS key for the Elasticsearch HTTP interface.\n\nNow I need to:\n1. Create a TLS secret for `es.example.com` in the elasticsearch namespace (for the ingress)\n2. Create an Ingress resource that:\n   - Routes HTTPS traffic for `es.example.com` to the `es-http` service on port 9200\n   - Redirects HTTP to HTTPS (so plain HTTP doesn't succeed)\n   - Uses the nginx ingress class\n\nSince Elasticsearch requires TLS on its backend, I'll need to configure the ingress to proxy HTTPS traffic to the backend rather than plain HTTP. This means adding an annotation to tell nginx to use HTTPS when communicating with the Elasticsearch service.\n\nFor the TLS setup, I need to decide between using an existing certificate or generating a self-signed one for `es.example.com`. Since we don't have a real CA, I'll generate a self-signed certificate. I should also consider how nginx will handle certificate verification when connecting to the Elasticsearch backend—by default it may not validate the backend certificate or will rely on its own CA bundle.\n\nMy approach will be to create a self-signed TLS certificate for the ingress frontend, store it in a Kubernetes secret, and then configure an Ingress resource with the appropriate annotations. For the backend connection to Elasticsearch, I can use the `nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/proxy-ssl-secret` annotation to pass the ES CA certificate for verification. Let me verify which nginx ingress controller version is available and what annotations it supports.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":595,"cache_read_input_tokens":29814,"cache_creation":{"epheme